    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for this house i'm looking at in toronto. i've never bought a place before so i'm kinda lost. can u explain what escrow actually is and why it's even used in the closing process?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of a real estate purchase, is essentially a neutral third party holding funds and documents until all the conditions of the sale are met. Think of it like a highly trusted, temporary holding tank for your money and the property papers. It's used to ensure that both you, the buyer, and the seller fulfill your respective obligations before the final exchange happens, which keeps the whole transaction safe and secure. This prevents any one party from getting the other's money or property and then running off with it, which is vital in a big deal like buying a home.",
