    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so like, who actually holds onto the money? is it a bank or something? and what happens if one of the parties tries to back out after the money is already in there?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The entity holding the money is typically a title company or an escrow agent, who are specialized professionals, not always a standard bank, though banks can facilitate it. They are bound by strict legal rules to manage those funds until the closing conditions are satisfied. If one party tries to back out after the money is in escrow, the escrow agent steps in as the referee, which is where the real complexity comes in. They follow the contract terms to determine what happens next, which could involve releasing the funds back to the buyer, or potentially triggering penalties or breach of contract clauses.",
      "source": "target",
